english:
  title: Account of the Life and Deeds of Minister Lee Saek, the Recluse of Mokeun
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Minister's name was Saek, styled Yeong-suk, with the pen name Mokeun. He was from Hanju in Chungcheong Province. His great-grandfather was posthumously appointed Minister of Personnel, and his grandfather received the rank of Court Historian. His father served as a high official and was known as a man of letters, receiving the posthumous name Mun-hyo.

    His father passed the imperial examination during the Yuan Dynasty and took the name Gajae. Twenty volumes of his collected works still circulate in the world. The Minister's mother was the Lady of Yoyang County, née Kim of Hamchang. She gave birth to him in the fifth lunar month of the year Muchen, according to the Tianhli calendar.

    From childhood, the Minister showed extraordinary brilliance. He could read and memorize at a glance. At fourteen, he passed the state examination with such distinction that prominent families all sought him as a son-in-law. When he came of age to marry, noble houses competed for his hand even on his wedding day.

    He married the daughter of a high Yuan official and studied at the National Academy for three years, absorbing the profound learning of the Middle Kingdom. He became especially versed in the principles of Neo-Confucianism. When his father passed away in the tenth lunar month, he observed full mourning rites with exemplary devotion.

    In the summer of the year Gyesa, King Gongmin held the state examination. The Minister placed first and was appointed to high office. That autumn, he passed the provincial examination as the top candidate and was sent to Beijing as an official envoy. There, the great scholars Ouyang Xuan and Wang Sicheng supervised the metropolitan examination, and the Minister again succeeded brilliantly. When he presented his policy essays before the throne, he was ranked second in the highest grade. The examination officials greatly praised his work, and he was appointed to the Hanlin Academy.

    Upon his return to Korea, King Gongmin appointed him to increasingly important positions in government and the court. The Minister served with distinction in the royal secretariat and the archives office. He worked tirelessly to improve state governance and education.

    When red-turbaned rebels invaded the capital, the Minister remained steadfastly at the King's side, sharing every hardship. His counsel proved invaluable in defending the realm, and he was rewarded with a document of merit and lands.

    In his capacity as superintendent of national education, the Minister gathered the finest scholars of the realm. He established the Sungmun Academy and revived the study of Neo-Confucianism throughout the land. Each day, students gathered to study the classics and debate their interpretations. The Minister, sitting among them with serene countenance, would resolve their doubts with precision and depth, always guiding them toward the teachings of Zhu Xi. The scholarly spirit of the East was thus greatly renewed, and students ceased their superficial memorization of words and phrases to penetrate the mysteries of mind, nature, and destiny.

    When the King personally examined the students, seven were advanced to the highest degree, and all praised the Minister's guidance. Later, when he administered the state examination, thirty-three men were selected through methods adopted from the great examination systems of China.

    Once, the King had begun construction of a great temple in homage to his departed princess, commanding vast resources. When the royal minister Ryu Taek remonstrated that this work brought calamity to the realm and should be abandoned, the King fell into great anger and imprisoned him. He then commanded the Minister to compose an edict condemning Ryu Taek. The Minister refused, saying: "I cannot use my brush to condemn an innocent man." The King grew more enraged, but the Minister calmly explained that Ryu Taek's remonstrance was but duty to the throne.

    The matter was brought before the King's close advisor, who acknowledged that Ryu Taek spoke truth, and the King's wrath gradually subsided. Ryu Taek and the others were released, and the Minister was honored with fresh appointment.

    For seven years, the Minister served as the King's closest counselor, participating in all matters of state. Though often dismissed through the intrigues of jealous rivals, he was repeatedly recalled, for the King valued his wisdom above all others. The King once told his attendants: "This man's learning penetrates to the very marrow. Even in the Middle Kingdom, few compare to him."

    When the King passed away, the Minister was overcome with grief and withdrew from public life for many years, writing poetry and essays, and devoting himself to Buddhist works in honor of the late sovereign. He lived simply, asking little of his household, and treated his servants with unfailing kindness and patience.

    Yet when the realm faced crisis, the Minister answered the call once more. He traveled to Beijing as an envoy, where the great emperor received him with exceptional honor. Upon his return, jealous courtiers brought false accusations against him. He was banished repeatedly to distant provinces, but each time he bore his fate with composure, declaring: "Life and death are heaven's concern. I follow the path of righteousness." The people said that wherever he was exiled, heaven itself seemed to work miracles—once, when he was imprisoned during heavy rains, a flood destroyed the very jail, yet the Minister remained unharmed.

    When a new king ascended the throne, the Minister was again recalled and restored to honor. In his final years, he retired to the mountains to escape the summer heat. As he was about to board a boat, illness seized him. When a monk came to chant prayers for his soul, the Minister waved him away, saying: "The principle of life and death holds no mystery for me." Soon after, he passed into the Great Repose.

    The King was deeply grieved. He suspended all court functions for three days, sent envoys to conduct funeral rites, and bestowed the posthumous name "Mun-jeong" (文靖—the Refined and Enlightened).

    The Minister's nature was luminous and profound. His learning was vast and precise. In all his dealings, he was clear and resolute, moved always by loyalty and compassion. In conversation and debate, he was incisive yet kind, never harsh. When meeting others, he bore himself with humility and warmth, his very presence radiating harmony, yet commanded such dignity that none dared presume familiarity. His countenance revealed neither joy nor anger, his character neither pride nor coarseness—he seemed a vessel of pure equilibrium.

    Though blessed with power and favor for many years, no arrogance clouded his bearing. Though later he suffered hardship and exile, his spirit never dimmed. Prison brought him no shame, nor did high office bring him pride. His virtue was unshakeable.

    The Minister fathered three sons. The eldest served as Vice Director of State Affairs. The second, also a high official, passed the examination and supervised the academy. Both died before their father. The third son became a court official.

    The Minister's collected works consist of thirty-five volumes of poetry and twenty volumes of prose. During the long years from the late Yuan through the Ming dynasty, he held the position of chief state author. His writings were praised repeatedly and proved invaluable to the realm. Yet when he fell from favor, his rivals assumed control of official documents, and in their incompetence, state diplomatic missives began to receive criticism from the throne—thus was the worth of the Minister's wisdom made evident even in his absence.

    It is lamentable that King Gongmin, though he honored the Minister greatly, failed to fully implement his counsel. The Minister rose to the highest office but was soon dismissed, only to suffer the mockery and rejection of lesser men. Thus his great learning in the art of governance was never fully realized—but this was the will of Heaven.
  footnotes:
